It seems that when a second volume is attached the svirt labeling on the first reverts to fixed_disk_device_t.

{code:title=Before}
brw-rw----. 1 system_u:object_r:svirt_image_t:s0:c21,c1018 qemu       qemu 8, 32 Jan 24 15:14 /dev/sdc
brw-rw----. 1 system_u:object_r:fixed_disk_device_t:s0 eucalyptus disk 8, 33 Jan 24 15:14 /dev/sdc1
{code}
{code:title=After}
brw-rw----. 1 system_u:object_r:fixed_disk_device_t:s0 eucalyptus disk 8, 33 Jan 24 15:14 /dev/sdc1
brw-------. 1 system_u:object_r:fixed_disk_device_t:s0 eucalyptus root 8, 32 Jan 24 15:15 /dev/sdc
brw-rw----. 1 system_u:object_r:svirt_image_t:s0:c21,c1018 qemu       qemu 8, 48 Jan 24 15:15 /dev/sdd
{code}

The untruncated version of that message is, "Warning! Received an indication that the LUN assignments on this target have changed. The Linux SCSI layer does not automatically remap LUN assignments."  Here are the relevant bits from the source code for kernel-3.10.0-514.6.1.el7:

{code:java}
} else if (sshdr->asc == 0x3f && sshdr->ascq == 0x0e) {
	evt_type = SDEV_EVT_LUN_CHANGE_REPORTED;
	scsi_report_lun_change(sdev);
	sdev_printk(KERN_WARNING, sdev,
		    "Warning! Received an indication that the "
		    "LUN assignments on this target have "
		    "changed. The Linux SCSI layer does not "
		    "automatically remap LUN assignments.\n");
} else if (sshdr->asc == 0x3f)
{code}

Perhaps scsi_report_lun_change eventually causes the change events we see.
